The basic business model of an activist short seller is:
=09Investigate a company, ideally using only public sources.
  [1]

=09Find out that the company is bad.=09Short its stock.=09Put out a public =
report describing your findings =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthis company is bad=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0in a zippy, emphatic, hopefully accurate way.=09Wa=
tch the stock go down, because people read your report, realize that the co=
mpany is bad=C2=A0and dump the stock.=09Profit, by covering your short at t=
he new, lower market price reflecting the new, accurate, bad information th=
at you have published about the company.
  [2]



Obviously some short sellers, sometimes, will deviate from this ideal model=
. They will investigate a company using nonpublic information, for instance=
, or their report will be inaccurate. But assuming that they follow the ide=
al model: Is this okay? Are you allowed to do this?
In the US, I think the answer is clearly yes, but people do get mad about i=
t. There is some apparent intuition that it is market manipulation: You are=
 betting that a stock will fall, and then you are=C2=A0making=C2=A0it fall =
(by publishing your report), and that seems somehow like cheating. In pract=
ice, most people who don=E2=80=99t like it will complain that the report is=
 inaccurate =E2=80=94=C2=A0it is more clearly market manipulation if the re=
port is wrong =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I think that some of this really is driven=
 by suspicion of the whole business model. Even if the report is entirely a=
ccurate and based on public information, something about the model strikes =
people as icky.
Here is a slight complication of that business model:
=09Investigate a company, ideally using only public sources.=09Find out tha=
t the company is bad.=09Write a report=C2=A0describing your findings =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthis company is bad=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0in a zippy, e=
mphatic, hopefully accurate way.=09
Sell=C2=A0that report to some other, larger, better capitalized hedge fund.=
=09
That=C2=A0fund shorts the stock.=09You publish the report.=09Watch the stoc=
k go down, because people read your report, realize that the company is bad=
=C2=A0and dump the stock.=09The other hedge fund profits, by covering its s=
hort at the new, lower market price reflecting the new, accurate, bad infor=
mation that you have published about the company.=C2=A0=09It gives you a cu=
t of the profits.

This is a more complicated model, but it makes more sense given the economi=
c and social reality of activist short selling:
=09If you are an activist short seller, you are normally pretty specialized=
: Finding and investigating bad companies is your calling, and you=E2=80=99=
re not also out there making tons of deep-value long bets or whatever.
  [3]

=09Stocks mostly go up, so it is hard to run a hedge fund that only makes s=
hort bets: Who would want to invest?
  [4]

=09Also it is=C2=A0just possible=C2=A0that the personal characteristics tha=
t make=C2=A0you a good activist short seller (cynicism, combativeness) will=
 also make you bad at raising money from clients.=09So if you=E2=80=99re go=
od at identifying bad companies and writing punchy reports about how they=
=E2=80=99re bad, you might not be in a position to make a big bet on your r=
eport, because you just don=E2=80=99t have a lot of capital.
  [5]

=09Meanwhile plenty of other, bigger hedge funds would love to have some go=
od short ideas, but don=E2=80=99t want to pay a full-time analyst to go aro=
und digging for frauds. They=E2=80=99ll happily give you a share of the win=
nings if you bring them your ideas.

What about this model? I think people find it even ickier. In particular, t=
here is something about the=C2=A0collusion=C2=A0between the short researche=
r and the hedge fund that rubs people the wrong way. Surely it is unfair fo=
r the hedge fund to trade on the researcher=E2=80=99s report before it is p=
ublished. The report is nonpublic information (it hasn=E2=80=99t been publi=
shed yet), and it is material (if it causes the stock to go down), so isn=
=E2=80=99t it insider trading for the hedge fund to trade on it?
Again, I think that the answer in US law is no, this is fine. Insider tradi=
ng,=20
I like to say, is not about fairness; it=E2=80=99s about theft. It=E2=80=99=
s illegal to trade on material nonpublic information that you get in violat=
ion of some duty to someone; trading on your own=C2=A0information =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0like =E2=80=9CI am about to publish this report=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0is fine. Here, the short researcher owns the information (the report), a=
nd=C2=A0wants=C2=A0the hedge fund to trade, so it=E2=80=99s fine. But I sho=
uld stress:
=09Nothing here is legal advice.=09It icks people out, even if it is legal,=
 and there are constant rumors of US investigations into collusion among sh=
ort sellers.=09The US has somewhat unusual insider trading rules, and in ot=
her countries there is more of a risk that=C2=A0any=C2=A0trading on materia=
l nonpublic information might be illegal.

Last year, US activist short research firm Hindenburg Research published a =
