<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose a model of a large private equity fi=
rm would be:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It is a conglomerate with an equity v=
alue of hundreds of billions of dollars, perhaps <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35934584.195413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxhY2tzdG9u=
ZS5jb20vdGhlLWZpcm0vIzp-OnRleHQ9QmxhY2tzdG9uZSUyMGlzJTIwdGhlJTIwd29ybGQncyU=
yMGxhcmdlc3QsYnVzaW5lc3NlcyUyMHRoYXQlMjBkZWxpdmVyJTIwbGFzdGluZyUyMHZhbHVlLg=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa68db5e4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a trillion dollars</a>.</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It is extremely acquisitive, buying lots =
of new companies each year.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It use=
s a lot of leverage: It borrows money to pay for those acquisitions.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It constantly needs to=C2=A0<em>raise =
equity.=C2=A0</em>Most hundred-billion-dollar companies just have stock out=
standing, and buy some back sometimes, but rarely sell more. But private eq=
uity firm runs funds with=C2=A0limited lifespans, so it has to keep raising=
 more money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">All of these activiti=
es =E2=80=94=C2=A0the acquisitions, the borrowing, the equity raising =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0are reasonably complex and bespoke; borrowing to fund a leverag=
ed buyout is more complicated and expensive than issuing an investment-grad=
e bond.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Its staffing is quite lean=
, with just a few thousand employees managing all those acquisitions and fu=
ndraisings.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This makes big private equity firms the best p=
ossible clients for a lot of professional service providers: They are enorm=
ous, they are constantly doing stuff, the stuff is complex and labor-intens=
ive, and they don=E2=80=99t have enough employees to do it in-house. So the=
y have to employ lots of outside service providers, accountants and consult=
ants and bankers and lawyers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also private equity firms are sometimes less f=
ocused on cost discipline than the average, you know, industrial company: P=
rivate equity firms are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/35934584.195413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjQtMDMtMTQvYXBvbGxvLXBhcnRuZXItZGlkLXRoZS1vay1raW5kLW9mLWZyYXVkP2Nt=
cGlkPUJCRDA3MDIyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXd=
zbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDcwMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB2c12c5ce" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">pretty good at passing on professional expe=
nses</a> to their investors, and the private equity employees are all prett=
y well paid so they=E2=80=99re not going to begrudge their professionals ma=
king a bit of money for themselves.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so the most lucrative skill for a lawyer i=
n the US in 2024 is probably less =E2=80=9Cknowing law=E2=80=9D and more =
=E2=80=9Cknowing private equity firms.=E2=80=9D At the New York Times, <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35934584.195413/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyNC8wNy8wMS9idXNpbmVzcy9sYXctZmlybS1wYXktc2FsY=
XJ5Lmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5f0ee45d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Maureen Farrell and A=
nupreeta Das report</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hotshot Wall Street lawyers are now so in dema=
nd that bidding wars between firms for their services can resemble the fren=
zy among teams to sign star athletes.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Eight-figure pay packages =E2=80=94 rare a dec=
ade ago =E2=80=94 are increasingly common for corporate lawyers at the top =
of their game, and many of these new heavy hitters have one thing in common=
: private equity.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In recent years, highly profitable private equ=
ity giants like Apollo, Blackstone and KKR have moved beyond company buyout=
s into real estate, private lending, insurance and other businesses, amassi=
ng trillions of dollars in assets. As their demand for legal services has s=
kyrocketed, they have become big revenue drivers for law firms. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lawyers with close ties to private equity incr=
easingly enjoy pay and prestige similar to those of star lawyers who repres=
ent America=E2=80=99s blue-chip companies and advise them on high-profile m=
ergers, takeover battles and litigation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last year, six partners at Kirkland [&amp; Ell=
is LLP], including some who were recruited during the year, each made at le=
ast $25 million, according to people with knowledge of the arrangements who=
 weren=E2=80=99t authorized to discuss pay publicly. Several others in its =
London office made around $20 million.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One partner at a law firm said pay for top law=
yers had roughly tripled in the past five years.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As a former corporate law associate, I cannot =
deny that I am envious, though my feelings are complicated. If you are a la=
w firm partner getting paid $25 million for working on private equity, it=
=E2=80=99s not because you are billing $25,000 per hour for <em>your </em>t=
ime. It=E2=80=99s because you are <em>generating=C2=A0</em>work for an abso=
lute army of associates, who are working all night on your deals.</p>
